There was a recent court case on this subject whose appeal was heard in the First Circuit Court of Appeals, in Boston's lovely Moakley Courthouse.  The suit had been brought by a variety of people, including a few members of the military, parents of a few members of the military (heh), and a few other people I can't remember.  It aimed to block a military action against Iraq, on the grounds that there had been no formal declaration of war.<br>
The three-judge panel ruled in favor of the government.  They wrote:<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> The case before us is a somber and weighty one. We have considered these important concerns carefully, and we have concluded that the circumstances call for judicial restraint. The theory of collision between the legislative and executive branches is not suitable for judicial review, because there is not a ripe dispute concerning the President's acts and the requirements of the October Resolution passed by Congress. By contrast, the theory of collusion, by its nature, assumes no conflict between the political branches, but rather a willing abdication of congressional power to an emboldened and enlarged presidency.<br>
That theory is not fit for judicial review for a different, but related, reason: Plaintiffs' claim that Congress and the President have transgressed the boundaries of their shared war powers, as demarcated by the Constitution, is presently insufficient to present a justiciable issue. Common to both is our assessment that, before courts adjudicate a case involving the war powers allocated to the two political branches, they must be presented with a case or controversy that clearly raises the specter of undermining the constitutional structure.  <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
In other words, since the Legislative and Executive branches are in agreement on the issue of whether or not military action is a good idea, the conflict between the branches isn't well-enough defined to rule on.  As a historical note, a similar challenge made well into the Vietnam War was rejected for similar reasons.  In that case, the fact that Congress had approved funding for the &quot;war&quot; year after year served as evidence of their tacit approval of it.<br>
As has been documented elsewhere, I have few kind words to say about the justifications that were given for invading Iraq, I think this decision is fine.  Some may see it as a cop-out, but I have mostly good things to say about the idea of judicial restraint.<br>
The opinion, which I am unfortunately only able to find in PDF format, <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.ca1.uscourts.gov/pdf.opinions/03-1266-01A.pdf">is here</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->.<br>
Regarding the original question, I don't understand why impeaching the president is even an option.  Congress passes unconstitutional stuff all the time, and even if it is struck down by the court, the people responsible remain in office.  I suppose that would be the short answer. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub40.ezboard.com/bthesaryrntavern.showUserPublicProfile?gid=eudamanslayer>EudaManslayer</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle><span style='color:orange;'>Tavern Resident</span></span><br>  Posts: 1180<br> <font color=#6FB8DD>(4/14/03 11:07 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub40.ezboard.com/fthesaryrntavernthefurnace.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3207.topic&index=74>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Doe, et al. v Bush</span><hr size=1> was there a decleration of war vs Veitnam? Did we need a war to land in Panama and trap Noeraga in a convent and play bad music to drag him out?<br>
